								<div class="title" id="post-title-4688531">
																		PF should use a more gradated rating system
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zzuxon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1496981); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1496981&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226595" alt="Zzuxon" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1496981)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zzuxon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1496981); return false;" >Zzuxon</a></span> <span class="odate time_1592179507 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Jun 2020 00:05</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4688531">
									

<p><strong>Description:</strong> I believe PF should have a rating module which offers 7 options as opposed to the current 2: -3, -2, -1, +0, +1, +2, and +3. When importing existing wiki content, I would treat all existing -1s and +1s as -2s and +2s respectively, and new user guides would emphasize that +2 and -2 are the &quot;default&quot; expression of approval/disapproval, with the 1s and 3s being more or less extreme versions. Deletions guidelines would be adjusted accordingly.</p>
<p><strong>Reason:</strong> A -1/+1 binary is far too simple and uninformative for the work we do on the site. I cannot reflect the difference between a work I find to be truly exceptional and a work I only barely consider good in the work's rating, nor can I distinguish a poorly conceived coldpost and something with real potential that just falls short. Worst of all, I cannot tell an author that I read their work and consciously decided not to change the rating one way or another, except with a &quot;novote&quot; comment, which is an issue as I generally couldn't articulate why I decided to novote. As an author, I would love to know how many people no-voted on my own works.</p>
<p><strong>Advantages:</strong> This would promote a more critical userbase. There are MANY times I've read an SCP that I consider to be competent but very mediocre. On some level I understand the wiki would be better off if works like these were not on it, but I simply cannot bring myself to downvote. It feels too rude to me to essentially say such a work should be booted off the wiki. However if I had a less severe version of a downvote (a -1 as opposed to the more standard -2), I know I would be more comfortable using it, and in doing so promote a higher standard of work. Another situation I often find myself in is reading an SCP I know is highly flawed but has a few elements that I find so interesting or compelling that I feel I must upvote it. As it stands, my +1 entirely cancels the -1 of a more critical site member. But under my proposed system, I would give it only a +1, as opposed to the more standard +2, in recognition of its faults. Now a more critical user's -2 or -3 can overtake my vote's influence. Based on certain recent discussions on the philosophy of novotes and downvotes I've seen, I know I'm not alone in voting in this fashion, I saw experienced, prolific authors express feelings much like my own.<br />
This system would also help author's get a much better idea of how much their audience enjoyed the work, rather than a mere liked it/didn't like it binary.</p>
<p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong> The intuitive sense for the &quot;value&quot; of a rating that site users have developed over the years will no longer be valid and will have to be adjusted. Treating the new +2 and -2 as being equivalent to the old +1 and -1 essentially halves the value of each rating point.<br />
People may be inclined to treat +1 and -1 the same way they have been on wikidot, with +/-2 being an extreme version and +/-3 being an extra extreme version. This could perhaps be corrected by making only +/-2 and +0 available on the rating module by default, with the 1s and 3s available via a small pulldown menu, to indicate they should be used less often. It could also be corrected by making the new system -1.5, -1.0, -.5, +0, +.5, +1.0, and +1.5.<br />
Users transferring to the new site would be unlikely to go through all their existing +/-1s (Now +/-2s) and adjust them according to the new system. Consequently, the rating system would not have quite the same meaning for works originally made on wikidot as it would for works made on the new site.</p>

							</div>

								
					
