								<div class="title" id="post-title-4689711">
																		Re: PF should use a more gradated rating system
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zzuxon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1496981); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1496981&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226595" alt="Zzuxon" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1496981)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zzuxon" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1496981); return false;" >Zzuxon</a></span> <span class="odate time_1592283358 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 Jun 2020 04:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4689711">
									

<p>You raise interesting points.</p>
<p>I'll start by saying that on further reflection, even before I read your response, I would make 2 adjustments to my initial proposal: moving to the .5/1/1.5 scale I mentioned in the disadvantages portion, and removing the extreme downvote (-1.5) option entirely. I think the .5/1/1.5 scale greatly reduces or eliminates the 1st and 3rd points I listed in disadvantages and other similar psychological effects my proposal would have by reducing the perceived impact on the rating system. I would remove the extreme downvote because distinguishing between a bad article and a very bad article seems much less valuable than distinguishing between a good article and an extremely good article, and the extreme downvote's usefulness for malicious downvoting would far outweigh whatever usefulness it has.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Malicious downvoters, and anyone who thinks of a downvote as &quot;I don't want this on the site&quot;, will always pick -3. Malicious upvoters, and anyone who thinks of an upvote as &quot;this should stay on the site&quot;, will always pick +3.</p>
<p>Those who think critically will be picking their votes in the middle ranges, and therefore their opinions may literally count for less than those who think less critically. I don't think that's a mindset we want to encourage.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is a good point. But what do you think of the pull down menu concept? I feel that putting -.5, +.5, and +1.5 behind an optional menu powerfully conveys through design that they shouldn't be routinely used. And for people who aren't thinking very much about how they vote, I feel even that small extra step would go a long way to keeping them using the default +1/-1 and +0 options. If it's ever decided that the barrier to the more selective options needs to be bigger, the expanded rating module could be opened in a new tab, further driving home the point &quot;Only use these if you REALLY want to.&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Being able to adjust the intensity of your vote won't help you express a conflicted opinion, it just makes your vote weaker.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is true that it makes my vote weaker, but since my approval of the work is also weaker than usual, my vote being weaker in this scenario feels appropriate to me.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The most useful thing you can do in this situation is leave a comment explaining your thoughts - a more nuanced rating system won't help the author. .</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The issue is that in these situations the comment explaining my thoughts would pretty much always look like &quot;This is competently written and not egregiously uninteresting, but it also doesn't really do anything for me. Novote.&quot; I usually couldn't articulate why I felt this way. Using a more nuanced system may not help the author very much, but a comment like that isn't helpful at all. Of course, being able to quickly and conveniently send that sort of message is the benefit of an active novote button, which I would certainly make use of, but a -.5 lets me help disincentivize extremely mediocre work in a way that doesn't feel as aggressive or rude.</p>

							</div>

								
					
